Notes:
I stepped up towards the top section of the curving crack.  This made it very strenuous and scary, as I couldn't place further gear until I got round the corner.  
If I do this again, sus out what cam I can place where before making the move up, but preferably, instead of moving up, stay low, which the pair after us, said was much more enjoyable!!

when I get up to the 4/5 bolt, the sequence that worked was high left foot on ledge on the left, reach up with left hand to the top of the hold that has a side pull, move right hand to the side pull (so it's sitting below and left of the left hand, pull up on these and reach up to the juggy flake hold, then bring right foot up
first section is hard, big move from break to jug up on the left
Look out for the right foot wide on the right after moving right at the 2nd/3rd clip.  Once I'd seen this I was able to reach up and continue the climb

managed the sit start, but couldn't move up to the top.  Try using the undercling with the RH to move up.
Tried to go up it again on TR to do it clean and could make the last crux move to get above the jug into the corner!!!

- use left foot to brace off to get off the ground
- when moving the left foot up to the first ledge - use the undercling just above the sloper for the right hand.
- when moving up from here drop right hand down to sloper, the first time I made this move I got my weight over my left foot and could reach up to the flake direct (neater); alternatively, there are also holds on the right that I used on another attempt. 
- I think there are two ways to progress past the jug to the corner - today I managed it by lay backing to the left, getting my feet up on the right and on the flake, moving my right hand up to the side pull and then moving up to the jug.  I think last time I climbed this I moved my feet out left and maybe just bunched up and bumped my left hand up for the jug?
- once I've got this the rest is relatively straightforward!

of the two paths described in the guide, start from where the upper one crosses the stream (we started where lower one crosses and had to retrace our steps). Third part of the day, finishing at 8pm.  We went off route from the second pitch, leading to some long run-outs for both Matt and me, which wasn't great.  From the grassy level below the slab the route goes up the central crack initially, then out left to the edge of the arete, then up and over the spikes.  That way you get more protection.  John said when you were on the route you could tell you were on it from wear.
